  "prompt": "Any good books to develop a statistical background? For a math major wanting to get more into stats",
  "response": "Certainly! Here are several books that would help you build a strong statistical background, especially as a math major:\n\n1. **\"Statistical Inference\" by George Casella and Roger L. Berger**  \n   This book provides a thorough introduction to the theoretical aspects of statistics, covering estimation, hypothesis testing, and more. It's rigorous and suitable for someone with a math background.\n\n2. **\"The Elements of Statistical Learning\" by Trevor Hastie, Robert Tibshirani, and Jerome Friedman**  \n   This is a great resource if you're interested in machine learning and data mining. It covers a variety of statistical methods and is accessible for readers with a strong math foundation.\n\n3. **\"Introduction to the Theory of Statistics\" by Mood, Graybill, and Boes**  \n   This classic text covers the fundamentals of statistical theory, including point estimation, confidence intervals, and hypothesis testing with a solid mathematical foundation.\n\n4. **\"All of Statistics: A Concise Course in Statistical Inference\" by Larry Wasserman**  \n   This book is an excellent overview of statistics for those who have a math background. It covers both theoretical and applied aspects in a concise manner.\n\n5. **\"Mathematical Statistics with Applications\" by Dennis Wackerly, William Mendenhall, and Richard L. Scheaffer**  \n   This book combines theory with applications, making it a good fit for someone looking to understand statistical methods in practice.\n\n6. **\"Bayesian Data Analysis\" by Andrew Gelman et al.**  \n   If you're interested in Bayesian statistics, this book provides a comprehensive introduction while emphasizing practical applications and real data analysis.\n\n7. **\"Statistical Modeling: A Fresh Approach\" by David Freedman**  \n   This book offers a more conceptual approach to statistics, emphasizing the understanding of statistical models in real-world applications.\n\n8. **\"Mathematical Statistics\" by Jun Shao**  \n   This book provides a modern treatment of mathematical statistics, including topics like asymptotic theory and advanced hypothesis testing.\n\n9. **\"Applied Linear Statistical Models\" by Kutner, Nachtsheim, Neter, and Li**  \n   This is an excellent resource for understanding linear regression and ANOVA, with practical applications and examples.\n\n10. **\"The Art of Statistics: Learning from Data\" by David Spiegelhalter**  \n    This book is more accessible and focuses on the application of statistics to real-world problems, helping to build intuition.\n\nThese books range from theoretical to applied statistics, so you can choose based on your interests and background. Happy reading!",
